text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Accentism towards Filipino nurses%0a%0a:Author: sgangu%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aA group of Filipino nurses were mocked for their accents. %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThis case of language discrimination actually came to light in the form of a lawsuit. It involves 69 immigrants who were constantly mocked for their accent in a California hospital. Bosses and coworkers allegedly listened in on their conversations with each other and harassed them for their accents. They were also prohibited from speaking Tagalog to each other within the hospital. Apparently security guards were assigned to keep an eye on them and report if they saw them speaking in Tagalog with each other. %0a%0aIn this case, speaking a non-English language itself is seen as unprofessional. Additionally, the way that Filipino immigrants speak English is also being mocked. %0aAs a matter of fact, there is no standard Filipino accent because of the range of languages spoken in the country. It ranges from standard American english because the Philippines has been an American colony to a Filip-Tagalog accent. In this accent, there is no tap sound in words like "butter" and the word is actually spoken like two discrete words, such as 'bʌt.təɹ'. In this case, the linguistic discrimination seems to have occurred for no other purpose but the sake of discriminating because Manila english is just as comprehensible as standard American english. This is an example of where prescriptivism can be harmful and discriminatory towards demographics that do not speak the superstratum language. %0a%0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://www.latimes.com/health/la-xpm-2012-sep-18-la-me-english-only-20120918-story.html%0a%0ahttps://www.dialectsarchive.com/philippines-3%0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210507-015829-958480#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Philippine English as a dialect of English %0a-> - david_h%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aOne of the reasons why the Filipino accent sounds weird to native speakers of Standard American English is because Philippine English is a distinct dialect. Similar to how some American dialects allow certain grammatical rules to be bent, Philippine English does have its own set of quirks that non-speakers would find strange.%0a%0aI like the point given above that Filipinos are influenced by the range of languages spoken in the Philippines. In an article from the Oxford English Dictionary announcing the addition of Philippine English words, influences from local languages like Tagalog are augmented with influence from foreign languages like Hokkien, Tamil, English, Spanish, and Catalan. These interactions create new words that are used in everyday speech in the Philippines. The author of the article, Dr. Danica Salazar, %0aa linguist and an editor of World Englishes for the OED, encouraged fellow speakers of the Filipino accent to not worry about conforming to Standard American or British English (prescriptivism), citing how many accepted English varieties were once adaptations of another English dialect.%0a%0a%0ahttps://public.oed.com/blog/philippine-english-in-the-september-2018-update/%0a%0ahttps://news.abs-cbn.com/ancx/culture/spotlight/08/22/20/what-is-philippine-english-and-why-should-pinoys-stop-looking-down-on-it%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210507-015829-958480#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210501-064445-216490#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-30.04.2021 - 23:44-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210501-064445-216490 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!Abi_S%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''stereotypes in workplace'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aI wonder if people also think they're less capable due to their accent %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210501-064445-216490#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: A:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
