diff:1620352708:1619851484:=56,72c56%0a%3c #foxbegin 210507-015829-958480#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Philippine English as a dialect of English %0a%3c -> - david_h%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c One of the reasons why the Filipino accent sounds weird to native speakers of Standard American English is because Philippine English is a distinct dialect. Similar to how some American dialects allow certain grammatical rules to be bent, Philippine English does have its own set of quirks that non-speakers would find strange.%0a%3c %0a%3c I like the point given above that Filipinos are influenced by the range of languages spoken in the Philippines. In an article from the Oxford English Dictionary announcing the addition of Philippine English words, influences from local languages like Tagalog are augmented with influence from foreign languages like Hokkien, Tamil, English, Spanish, and Catalan. These interactions create new words that are used in everyday speech in the Philippines. The author of the article, Dr. Danica Salazar, %0a%3c a linguist and an editor of World Englishes for the OED, encouraged fellow speakers of the Filipino accent to not worry about conforming to Standard American or British English (prescriptivism), citing how many accepted English varieties were once adaptations of another English dialect.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c https://public.oed.com/blog/philippine-english-in-the-september-2018-update/%0a%3c %0a%3c https://news.abs-cbn.com/ancx/culture/spotlight/08/22/20/what-is-philippine-english-and-why-should-pinoys-stop-looking-down-on-it%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210507-015829-958480#%0a---%0a> %0a
